commits.message:
🚀 Implement complete 44agents Chrome Extension for AI-powered n8n workflow generation

## ✨ Features Implemented

### 🏗️ Core Infrastructure
- Chrome Extension structure with manifest.json v3
- Content script for n8n page detection and UI injection
- Background service worker for API management and authentication
- Floating chat interface with n8n-themed design and animations

### 🤖 Multi-AI Integration
- Modular AI service abstraction layer
- Claude (Anthropic) API integration with streaming support
- OpenAI GPT API integration with JSON mode
- Google Gemini API integration with large context window
- Smart AI model selection based on complexity and cost optimization

### ⚡ Advanced Workflow Generation
- Context-aware workflow generation pipeline with 7-step process
- Intelligent prompt engineering with provider-specific optimization
- Comprehensive workflow validation and compatibility checking
- Multiple import methods: clipboard, direct API, and file download
- Workflow enhancement with error handling and documentation

### 💾 Data Management & Storage
- Persistent chat history with conversation threading
- Secure API key storage using Chrome storage API
- Configuration management with user preferences
- Usage metrics tracking (costs, tokens, success rates)
- Export/import functionality for data portability
- Automatic cleanup and retention policies

### 🎨 User Experience
- Modern popup interface for configuration and settings
- Real-time API key validation with status indicators
- Dark/light theme support with auto-detection
- Responsive design for different screen sizes
- Comprehensive error handling with user-friendly messages
- Loading states and progress indicators

### 📊 Analytics & Monitoring
- Usage statistics by AI provider
- Cost tracking and optimization
- Success rate monitoring
- Performance metrics collection
- Error logging and debugging support

## 🏛️ Architecture

### File Structure
- `manifest.json` - Chrome extension configuration
- `content.js/css` - n8n page integration and UI
- `popup.html/js` - Settings and configuration interface

issue.title: Internal error occurred: failed calling webhook "mcluster.kb.io"
issue.body:
I get following error trying to create a new PGSQL cluster:
Error from server (InternalError): error when creating "test.yaml": Internal error occurred: failed calling webhook "mcluster.kb.io": failed to call webhook: Post "https://cnpg-webhook-service.cnpg-system.svc:443/mutate-postgresql-cnpg-io-v1-cluster?timeout=10s": x50
9: certificate signed by unknown authority

Yesterday I've upgraded CNPG to 1.21. Upgrade went smoothly but we stared to have problem connectiong all new clusters via network (we could still connect to ones created with previous CNPG version: 1.20.2). I tried different user account.
So I've decided to revert to CNPG 1.20.02.
After downgrade I've started to get errors like above and cannot provision any new cluster.
Going again back to 1.21 also didn't help.
I discussed the issue with @leonardoce  on slack and He noticed that there is no caBundle in operator's mutating webhook.
I've tried to remove both operator, all it's webhooks and even cnpg-operator namespace and recreate it but with no luck.

issue.title: Stagger multiport bench per IP
issue.body:
**I am testing this now**

## Problem

Gravity benchmarks UPnP nodes at the same time across the network. This is a large problem for speedtesting as we are effectively DDoSing many servers as we are testing them all at the same time. Especially nodes with huge throughput rates.

The reason this is done is to check all nodes on the same hypervisor to make sure they aren't allocating resources they don't have. I.e. 8 Nimbus nodes sharing a 50Mbps connection.

## Solution

Use the IP of the node as a proxy for the Hypervisor (and upstream network connection). This isn't perfect as people can run multiple IPs on the same Hypervisor but it's pretty good.

Instead of running all nodes on the same block - we now group them by ip and run them at random times over 1 hour. I.e. If an operator is running 16 nodes on 2 different ips, all 8 nodes on IP 1 will run at a a random time between 0-3600 seconds, and all 8 nodes on IP B will also run at a random time between 0-3600.

The random time is the SAME for each of the nodes on the same ip. I.e. - the random timer is seeded.

The Potato block is still the trigger that starts the timers that run the multiport bench. So all nodes will have completed the multiport bench within 1 hour of the Potato block

## Random distribution

Here is the distribution across buckets (each bucket is 1000, i.e. 0-999, 1000-1999 etc) with 10000 random numbers:

```
Map(10) {
  0 => 983,
  1 => 992,
  2 => 996,
  3 => 995,
  4 => 1013,
  5 => 1027,
  6 => 1002,
  7 => 993,
  8 => 1020,
  9 => 979
}
```
